def: The quality of being formidable, or adapted to excite dread.Boyle.
Having, or consisting of, a single chamber; -- said of alegislative assembly. [R.] F. Lieber.

Having great power of leaping or running; nimble; active. [U.S.& Local Eng.]She is as spry as a cricket. S. Judd (Margaret).If I'm not so large as you, You are not so small as I, And not halfso spry. Emerson.
Taking root on, or above, the ground; rooting from the stem, asthe trumpet creeper and the ivy.
Within or beneath a membrane; as, intermembranous ossification.
The quality or state of being turbulent; a disturbed state;tumult; disorder; agitation. Shak.The years of . . . warfare and turbulence which ensued. Southey.
A machine for forming threads. [Obs.] W. Tooke.
To remove the oil from. Dryden.
To be irritated; to fret. [R.] Chapman.
To cast aside; to put off; to doff. [Obs.]Canst thou so daff me Thou hast killed my child. Shak.
